title: For Sale:  Nacre QUIETPRO®: Tactical Hearing Protection & Ambient Noise Amplification
postcontent:
Description:

QUIETPRO® is a digital, lightweight tactical communication headset with built in intelligent adaptive hearing protection. Nacre has designed QUIETPRO® to protect your hearing and at the same time to preserve your situational awareness to support command, control and communication both in silent and noisy conditions.

The system seals the ear with a specially made noise protective canal tip and captures sound by using microphones and feeds these sounds into the control unit. The control unit analyses the sound,decides action and transmits wanted sound to the loudspeaker.

Bionic Hearing: The situational awareness capability of the QUIETPRO® enables the reproduction of external sounds within the headset. This allows the user to hear naturally without affecting the high noise reduction properties of the headset. Through amplification of the external sounds and digital filtering, the QUIETPRO® enables the user to hear sounds that would not be heard without the QUIETPRO®. 

Passive Noise Reduction: achieves a Noise Reduction Rating (NRR) of 29dB. 

Active Noise Reduction: can reduce the harmful effects of noise from weapons discharge or explosions by approx. 40dB.

Radio Connectivity: allows radio communications to and from attached radio or intercom systems (not included). Radio communication has 3 modes:
·        Push to Talk (PTT)
·        Voice on Command (VOX)
·        Open Mic (O.MIC)

YouTube Video Description: 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7rfHys9eVhU

Personal Testimony:

I tested my unit out on a back country road from the confines of my truck cab. I stopped the truck, rolled down the passenger window, and unloaded 10 rounds into the hillside while seated in the driver seat. All I heard was the slide action on my 9mm. 

Next, I tested it on a dove hunt with my boss. The goal was to see how it enhanced/hindered the user's situational awareness with multiple shooters. It muffled nearby shots while still providing ambient noise (wind, conversation, muffled gun shot, foot steps, etc) leaving my situational awareness unhindered by the gunfire.


Components Included:

·        Headset Cable
·        Canal Tips (3 pair: small, medium, & large)
·        Ear Anchors (2 pair: small & large)
·        Radio Cable(QP-Motorola XTS Series)
·        QUIETPRO® Control Unit
·        CR123A Lithium Batteries (2 non-rechargeable)
·        QUIETPRO® User Manual
·        QUIETPRO® Quick Reference Guide

New "tactical" 12 gauge. It's labeled "tactical" by the makers, but it's more of a short hunting length. Shot 3 boxes through it to break it in. Webley and Scott is an old English brand (Gen. Custer carried a Webley.) The original Webley closed and a company in Turkey obtained the name and all rights.

I have up for sale a milled Arsenal SA 93 Ak-47 with a chrome lined barrel, made in Bulgaria. This is a rare AK, and one of the best. It comes with 2-30 round mags, and a sling. These are highly desirable because they were a 100% Bulgarian-made Kalashnikovs with a milled receiver, and partially because they had the traditional 45 degree gas block and vented gas tube just as the original Type 3 AK-47 (AKK). Upon expiration of the Federal Assault Weapon Ban (9/19/2004), SA-93 owners could legally convert them back to military configuration and have a semi-automatic Bulgarian Type 3 AKK rifle. Aside from being a semi-automatic rifle, the only real difference from the military AK-47 was the stock set, lack of a lower tang, lack of a threaded barrel, and lack of a sling loop on the left/rear of the receiver. It is top of the line when it comes to AK's.

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W New Model No. 3 .38 Cal top break single-action revolver
postcontent:
This is a very rare historical piece. Several variants of this gun were produced, but this 3.5" barrel .38 S&W revolver is the rarest of them all. It's a top break single action revolver chambered in .38 S&W, which you can still buy and shoot today for around .5cents/round. 

A little history
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Smith & Wesson New Model No. 3 is a single-action revolver that was a redesign by Dan Wesson in 1877, after the Russian contracts for the No. 3 Russian were pretty much completed.

Barrel lengths are 3-1/2 (standard), 4, 5, 6, 6-1/2, 7, 7-1/2, and 8 (standard) inches. Chamberings include .44 S&W Russian, .32 S&W, .32-40 S&W, .38 S&W, .38-40, .38-44 S&W, .41 S&W, and .45 Webley. The finish is blue or nickel-plated, with hard rubber or walnut grips. The Smith & Wesson logo is molded into the rubber grips. .44 Russian with a 6-1/2 inch barrel is the most prevalent configuration. They were made from 1878 until 1912.

Retail values (with matching part numbers on frame, cylinder, barrel and latch):

Excellent: $3,420 - $10,200
Very Good: $2,160-$2,400
Good: $1,770-$1,950
Fair: $955-$1,590
Poor: $835
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This piece has all matching serial numbers and is in Good to Very Good condition (as rated by a professional gunsmith dealing in guns from this period). On top of the rarity of a piece such as this, the value increases significantly because it has such a low serial number, and because it has a rack-and-gear extractor.

It functions as it is supposed to and is in immaculate condition considering it's age. The retail prices above are the prices encountered if purchasing from an antique gun-shop; I'll start with a fair asking price of $2085 obo, the mid-range price of Good to Very Good condition.

More pictures: https://antiquefirearmsforsale.shutterfly.com/pictures/8
There is a slight handle ship to note, but it can be replaced cheaply and does not effect the value.
